<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1299636-did-anyone-think-that-the-writing-and">Did anyone think that the writing and vocabulary were quite advanced for someone who had no formal education?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1299636'><a id="like_count_community_question_1299636" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1299636?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">2 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F152519.Incidents_in_the_Life_of_a_Slave_Girl">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1299636-did-anyone-think-that-the-writing-and">3 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1299636-did-anyone-think-that-the-writing-and">See all 6 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/684405-ann-michael"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1442480472i/684405._UY100_CR1,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/684405-ann-michael">Ann Michael</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">No. Compared with the formal prose of the era, her writing seems &quot;simple&quot;...not flowery and educated with metaphor and lengthy vocabulary. People wrot<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">No. Compared with the formal prose of the era, her writing seems "simple"...not flowery and educated with metaphor and lengthy vocabulary. People wrote and spoke differently in the 1830s than they do today, and remember that she was essentially a house slave and heard the white people speaking--and that she would have read the books that educated whites kept, the Bible and Ovid and such. <br /><br />Her editor says that she did not change the author's language, but more her chronology and structure of the memoir. This I can believe, too.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
